<p>This is a figure from Hewitt's <em>Conceptual Physics</em> of how one sees oneself in a concave mirror:</p>
<p><a href="https://i.stack.imgur.com/4VPg1.gif" rel="nofollow noreferrer"><img src="https://i.stack.imgur.com/4VPg1.gif" alt="enter image description here"></a></p>
<p>If one would be beyond the center of curvature, one would see oneself upside down (and at the center, one's eye fills the whole spherical mirror).</p>
<p>Similar for objects behind the viewer, but it is a bit more difficult to do the raytracing. For a large experiment, see for example <a href="https://youtu.be/K_p5UoD6ljg" rel="nofollow noreferrer">this video</a> from the Exploratorium or <a href="https://videoportal.vm.uni-freiburg.de/video/G-244-abbildungsgesetz-mit-hohlspiegel-und-stift/aa63c1a1192bcfb7a4d434a25b0218e2" rel="nofollow noreferrer">this one from Freiburg</a>.</p>
